\end{keywords}

\section{Introduction}

Despite more than 40 years of observation and modelling, many features of {Gamma-Ray Bursts\xspace} (GRBs hereafter) still lack firm and unanimous explanations. 
The diversity and complexity of GRB prompt emission light curves is often used to illustrate the difficulty in the classification of these sources and in the unification of their properties. A natural approach to get insight into such complexity is to look for global and average properties, like flux time integral ({i.\,e.\xspace} \textit{fluence}), total duration, average spectrum, peak flux. Alternatively, one can try to break down the light curve into simpler parts following some pattern. If a fundamental building block was identified, the analysis of single blocks could be the key to the unification and disentanglement of properties of the underlying processes. Many authors \citep[{e.\,g.\xspace}][]{Imhof1974,Norris1986,Link1993,Ford1995,Kargatis1995,Liang1996,Preece1998,Ramirez-Ruiz1999,Lee2000,Ghirlanda2002,Lu2012,Basak2014} performed careful analyses of light curves and time resolved spectra looking for patterns and for hints about such fundamental building blocks. \citet{Norris1986} was presumably the first to systematically decompose the light curves into pulses and to look for patterns in the properties of these putative building blocks. Interest in such an approach grew in the following years, with a jump after \citet{Liang1996} established the existence of a clear correlation between spectral peak energy and flux during the decay of a pulse (usually referred to as the \textit{hardness-intensity correlation} \citep{Ryde1998}). \citet{Ryde2002} first set up a physical model of the decay phase of the pulse based on the idea that the emission comes from a relativistically expanding, spherical shell, which gives a simple explanation of the hardness-intensity correlation. The bottom line of such model is that the pulse decay is due to the arrival delay of photons emitted by high latitude parts of the shell, which are at a greater distance from the observer at the time of emission with respect to lower latitudes, due to the curvature of the emitting surface. Such effect is often referred to as the \textit{(relativistic) curvature effect}. In the following years, other authors \citep[{e.\,g.\xspace}][]{Dermer2004,Genet2009} proposed increasingly refined physical models of the pulse that include this effect. One overlooked aspect in all models so far, though, is the possibility that the pulse comes from a jet which is observed off-axis. In this work, we set up a simple version of the pulse model based on the curvature effect only, including for the first time the possibility of an off-axis viewing angle. 

The viewing angle, {i.\,e.\xspace} the angle between the jet axis and the line of sight, is usually assumed to be smaller than the jet semi-aperture, in which case the jet is said to be \textit{on-axis}. For larger viewing angles, {i.\,e.\xspace} for off-axis jets, the flux is severely suppressed because of relativistic beaming. Nevertheless, it can be still above detection threshold if the viewing angle is not much larger than the jet semi-aperture, especially if the burst is at low redshift. In \citet{2015MNRAS.447.1911P} we have shown that detectable off-axis jets might in fact dominate the low luminosity end of the observed population. 

The idea that nearby low luminosity GRBs could be off-axis events has been a subject of debate since the observation of GRB980425. \citet{Soderberg2004} rejected such possibility, based on radio observations of GRB980425 and GRB031203, but soon later \citet{Ramirez-Ruiz2005} presented an off-axis model for the afterglow of GRB031203 which seems to fit better the observations (including radio) with respect to the usual on-axis modelling. Using the same off-axis afterglow model, \citet{Granot2005a} extended the argument to two X-Ray Flashes, thus including them in the category of off-axis GRBs. \citet{2006MNRAS.372.1699G} argued that the off-axis interpretation of GRB031203 and GRB980425 is not practicable, because their true energy would then be on the very high end of the distribution, implying a very low likelihood when combined with the low redshift of these two events. More recently, the idea that such events are members of a separate class \citep[{e.\,g.\xspace}][]{Liang2007,Zhang2008,He2009,2011ApJ...739L..55B,Nakar2015} has gained popularity. Our results about the GRB luminosity function \citep{2015MNRAS.447.1911P}, though, still point towards the unification of these events together with ordinary GRBs based on the off-axis viewing angle argument. With the present work we address the issue from another point of view, by focusing on the apparently single pulsed, smooth behaviour of prompt emission light curves of these bursts, trying to figure out if such behaviour is expected in the case of an off-axis viewing angle.

The structure of the paper is as follows: in section \S\ref{sec:pulses-building-blocks} we briefly review some of the main arguments supporting the idea that the main driver of the pulse rise and decay is the curvature effect; in \S\ref{sec:pulse-light-curves} we discuss the main assumptions of our simple model and we present the predictions for a single pulse from an on-axis (\S\ref{sec:onaxis-jet}) and an off-axis jet (\S\ref{sec:offaxis-jet}), deferring detailed derivations to the appendix. In \S\ref{sec:multipulse} we build a superposition of pulses (to represent a synthetic prompt emission light curve) and show how its properties change with increasing off-axis viewing angle, comparing them with those found in light curve time resolved spectral analysis. Based on the obtained results, we conclude (\S\ref{sec:low-lum-grbs}) that light curves of low luminosity GRBs are consistent with the off-axis hypothesis. We then summarize and draw our conclusions in \S\ref{sec:conclusions}.


\section{Pulses: building blocks of GRB light curves}\label{sec:pulses-building-blocks}

\subsection{Pulses in the internal shock scenario}


The pulse width in GRB light curves is roughly constant throughout the burst duration \citep{Ramirez-Ruiz1999}. The internal shock scenario \citep{Rees1994} provides a natural framework for the understanding of this kind of behaviour. In this scenario, discontinuous activity in the central engine  produces a sequence of shells with random Lorentz factors. When faster shells catch up with slower ones, shocks develop and particles are heated. If the plasma is optically thin and some magnetic field is present, the energy gained by the electrons is promptly and efficiently radiated away by synchrotron (and inverse Compton) emission. Each pulse is thus the result of the merger of two shells beyond the photospheric radius $R_{ph}$. The strength of the shock, and thus the efficiency of the electron heating, depend strongly on the relative Lorentz factor of the merging shells (a radiative efficiency of a few percent is achieved only for $\Gamma_{\rm rel}\gtrsim 3$, \citet{Lazzati1999}). Shell pairs with small relative Lorentz factors merge later (they need more time to catch up with each other), thus the highest efficiency is achieved for shells merging just after the photospheric radius. This explains, within this framework, why the typical pulse width is not seen to grow with time: the bulk of the emission happens at a fixed radius, regardless of the expansion of the jet head.

\subsection{Angular time scale: a lower bound}
\label{sec:timescales}
Three main time scales arise in the internal shock scenario:
\begin{itemize}
 \item the shell crossing time $\tau_{sc}$, {i.\,e.\xspace} the time needed for the two shells to merge;
 \item the electron cooling time $\tau_{cool}$, {i.\,e.\xspace} the time needed by the electrons to radiate away most of the energy gained from the shock;
 \item the angular time scale $\tau_{ang}$, explained below.
\end{itemize}

The shell crossing time is $\tau_{sc}\sim w/\Gamma c$, where $w$ is the typical shell width. Being linked to the central engine activity, usually $w$ is assumed to be of the order of a few Schwarzschild radii. The Schwarzschild radius of a $5\,M_{\odot}$ black hole is $R_{s}\approx 1.5\times 10^{6}$~cm, thus $\tau_{sc}\sim 3\times 10^{-7}$~s~$w_6/\Gamma_2$, where we adopted the notation $Q_x = (Q/10^x)$ in cgs units. 
The electron cooling time scale, assuming synchrotron and/or Compton emission, is $\tau_{\rm cool} \sim 10^{-7}$~s for typical parameters\footnote{by typical parameters we mean $\Gamma = 100$, $\Gamma_{\rm rel} = 3$, $U_{\rm rad}=U_B$, a typical synchrotron frequency of $1$ MeV and we assume equipartition. See \citet{Ghisellini2000} and references therein for a complete treatment.} \citep{Ghisellini2000}. Both these time scales are far shorter than the angular time scale, which arises when one takes into account the arrival time difference of photons emitted at the same time by parts of the shell at different latitudes. Given that the typical photospheric radius $R_{ph}\gtrsim 10^{13}$~cm, this difference can be large: indeed $\tau_{ang} \sim R/\Gamma^2 c \approx 3 \times 10^{-2}$~s~$R_{13}/\Gamma_2^{2}$ and thus dominates over the other two.

This suggests that the rise and decay of the flux due to a single shell merger, {i.\,e.\xspace} the pulse, can not happen on a time scale smaller than $\tau_{ang}$, and can thus be dominated by the effect of shell curvature. 

\subsection{Independence from the internal shock scenario}

Being based solely on geometry and relativity, the above argument does not rely specifically on the (somewhat old fashioned) internal shock scenario. Any alternative model in which photons are produced at a large enough radius, being the photospheric radius \citep[{e.\,g.\xspace} subphotospheric dissipation models like those described in][]{2005ApJ...628..847R,Giannios2006,Beloborodov2010} or beyond \citep[{e.\,g.\xspace} magnetic reconnection models,][]{Lazarian2003,Zhang2011} eventually must take into account the arrival time delay of photons emitted by high latitude parts of the jet, and thus the angular time scale remains a lower bound on the light curve variability time scale.

