\subsection{Low luminosity GRBs}\label{sec:low-lum-grbs}
Recently, some authors \citep[{e.\,g.\xspace}][]{Liang2007,Zhang2008,He2009,2011ApJ...739L..55B} argued that a unique population of low luminosity {Gamma-Ray Bursts\xspace} exists, based on some common features of GRB060218, GRB980425, GRB031203 and GRB100316D. These features include, apart from the low inferred isotropic equivalent luminosity, an apparently single pulsed, smooth light curve (low variability), and a low average ${E_\mathrm{peak}}$. Since all such bursts were at a low redshift, the rate of like events per unit comoving volume in the Universe is very high (higher that that of ``normal'' GRBs), but we do not see the majority of these events because of selection effects.
The results discussed in this paper suggest that the apparently peculiar features of these GRBs can be interpreted instead as being just the indication that they were observed off-axis: figure~\ref{fig:offaxis-multi-lcs} together with results from the preceding sections show that their features are expected in the case of a jet seen off-axis. Moreover, in \cite{2015MNRAS.447.1911P} we have shown that the observed rate of low luminosity GRBs is consistent with what one would expect if they were just ordinary bursts seen off-axis (taking into account the fact that the de-beamed flux can still be above the instrument sensitivity if the off-axis viewing angle is not too large). Based on these considerations, we argue that there is no need to invoke a new separate population of low luminosity GRBs.

\section{Discussion and Conclusions}\label{sec:conclusions}


In this work we set up a simple physical model of a single GRB pulse based on shell curvature and relativistic effects only. Compared to other similar (and more refined) models \citep{Ryde2002,Dermer2004,Genet2009}, our model includes for the first time the effect of an off-axis viewing angle. The inclusion of such effect is of primary importance, because the probability to observe GRBs (slightly) off-axis is very high, given the typically narrow opening angle of their jets. Admittedly, the assumptions behind the model are at best a very rough approximation of reality: for example, the surface of a real jet is unlikely to be perfectly spherical; the jet borders are certainly not sharp; the emitting region is a volume, not a surface; the turning-on and turning-off of the emitting region can not be as sudden as assumed. Nevertheless, there are at least two reasons to take seriously the results of this simplified treatment: (i) all predictions are based on solid arguments which can be understood intuitively, and (ii) the general trend of the effect of the off-axis viewing angle does not depend on the simplifications adopted.

Given the above considerations, we divide our conclusions in two parts: those which are solid and do not depend much on the assumptions behind the model, and those which could change significantly if more realistic assumptions were made.

\begin{enumerate}
 \item Solid conclusions:
    \begin{enumerate}
    \item if the GRB jet is seen off-axis, single pulses appear longer and their spectrum appears softer than in the on-axis case;
    \item during the decay of the pulse, flux and spectral peak energy decrease in a correlated way, and the correlation is influenced by the viewing angle;
    \item if a burst is made up of a superposition of pulses, its variability is smeared out by pulse broadening if the jet is observed off-axis, with respect to the on-axis case;
    \end{enumerate}

 \item Conclusions that might be affected significantly by a change in the assumptions:
    \begin{enumerate}
    \item the spectral evolution during a single pulse is always hard-to-soft. An ``intensity-tracking'' behaviour can be obtained by superposition of pulses, especially if the viewing angle is off-axis, so that broadening of pulses favours their superposition;
    \item the shape of a pulse is qualitatively insensitive of the viewing angle.
    \end{enumerate}
\end{enumerate}

We plan to explore the effect of including an axisymmetric jet structure in the model (Salafia et al., in preparation) to test to which extent our results can be extended to the more realistic case of a jet with smooth borders.

As discussed in \S\ref{sec:low-lum-grbs}, the results support the idea that prompt emission properties of so-called low luminosity GRBs can be interpreted as indications that they are just ordinary bursts seen off-axis.


