Figure~\ref{fig:epeak-off-axis} shows the evolution of ${E_\mathrm{peak}}$ as a function of the flux $F$ during the pulse, for four different off-axis viewing angles. A ``hardness-intensity'' correlation during the pulse decay is still apparent, with a slightly steeper slope ($\sim 0.5$) just after the pulse peak, getting shallower as the flux decreases and eventually reaching $\sim 1/3$  as in the on-axis case. This slope difference is potentially a diagnostic of the viewing angle, whenever a sufficiently fine time resolved analysis is possible (there are other effects, though, which can affect this slope, as suggested {e.\,g.\xspace} in \citet{Genet2009} and \citet{Uhm2015}).


